## `updated_at` trigger

PostgreSQL **`DEFAULT now()`** on **`updated_at`** only applies on **INSERT**. To keep **`updated_at`** current on **UPDATE**, attach a **`BEFORE UPDATE`** trigger whenever a **`public`** table has an **`updated_at`** column.

### Shared trigger function

If the project already defines a trigger function (search migrations for e.g. **`set_updated_at`**, **`moddatetime`**, or **`handle_updated_at`**), **reuse it**. Otherwise create one once (in the same migration or an earlier one):

```sql
create or replace function public.set_updated_at()
returns trigger
language plpgsql
as $$
begin
    new.updated_at = now();
    return new;
end;
$$;
```

### When to attach

Whenever a migration **`CREATE TABLE … updated_at`** in **`public`** (or **`ALTER TABLE … ADD COLUMN updated_at`**), add a **`BEFORE UPDATE`** trigger on that table **in the same migration** (unless **`updated_at`** is intentionally unmanaged).

Prefer **idempotent** DDL: **`DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS … ON public.your_table`** then **`CREATE TRIGGER …`**. Use the **same trigger and function names** as elsewhere in the project when they exist.

### Example (replace names to match the project)

```sql
drop trigger if exists set_updated_at on public.your_table;

create trigger set_updated_at
    before update on public.your_table
    for each row
    execute function public.set_updated_at();
```

### Notes

- A one-time backfill migration may have attached triggers to **existing** tables; **new** tables still need the trigger when they are created later.
- For **partitioned** tables, confirm trigger behavior for your Postgres version (parent vs partitions — follow Postgres docs for your version).
